previous decades and have recently returned to Sydney. This particular example, painted in the Transport NSW livery, is operated by [[Hillsbus]].]]\nAs the Government has moved to a contestable contract model since the Unsworth report, so it has acquired a greater interest in the buses acquired to operate its routes. The NSW Government buys many of the new buses entering service in private operator fleets, and enjoys step-in rights where a private operator loses a contract. State Transit and the private operators must buy new vehicles from approved panel suppliers. These are [[Asia Motors]], [[Bustech]], [[Custom Coaches]], [[King Long|Heavy Vehicles Australia]], [[Hino Motors|Hino]], [[Iveco Bus|Iveco]], [[MAN Truck & Bus|MAN]], [[Scania AB|Scania]], [[Volgren]] and [[Volvo]].\n\nThe approved bus types are:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/operators/bus-coach|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711111540/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/operators/bus-coach|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-07-11|author=Transport for NSW|date=July 2015|title=Outer and metropolitan bus system bus specification guidelines}}</ref>\n\n* 14.5-metre two-door city bus, with a combined seating and standing capacity of 80\n* 18-metre articulated two- or three-door city bus, with a combined seating and standing capacity of 110\n* 12-metre two-door double deck city bus, with a combined seating and standing capacity of 90\n* 10-metre single-door 'mini' bus, with a combined seating and standing capacity of 40\n* 12.5-metre single-door city bus, with a combined seating and standing capacity of 65\n* 12.5-metre single-door school bus, with a combined seating and standing capacity of 70\n*[[File:Transport NSW liveried (mo 164), operated by Punchbowl Bus Co, Custom Coaches 'CB80' bodied Volvo B7RLE at Central station.jpg|alt=|thumb|250x250px|A [[Custom Coaches]] bodied Volvo B7RLE operated by private bus operator [[Punchbowl Bus Company]], which has adopted the standard TFNSW livery.]]12.5-metre two-door school bus, with a combined seating and standing capacity of 65.\n\nIn 2017 the government announced that [[articulated buses]] would be progressively phased out in favour of double-deckers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gerathy|first1=Sarah|last2=Raper|first2=Ashleigh|title=NSW Budget: New hospital, bus boost and roads planning announced with one week to go|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-06-13/nsw-budget-includes-tweed-hospital-bus-boost-and-roads-planning/8612746|accessdate=20 June 2017|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Livery ===\n[[File:Arncliffe railway station 20171004 04.jpg|thumb|upright|Bus, train and taxi signage at [[Arncliffe railway station]] adheres to the guidelines set by Transport for NSW.]]\nUntil 2010, each bus operator determined the livery for their vehicles. In late 2010, the NSW Government introduced a new livery for use on all new vehicles entering service on the network. The design is composed of a light blue ([[Pantone]] Matching System 297) background, a white chevron shape pointing in the direction of travel, and dark blue ([[Pantone]] Matching System 281) bumpers. Although there was some resistance from bus operators, including [[Forest Coach Lines]], who feared losing their brand identity, all operators had accepted the new requirements by 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/out-of-the-blue-an-illusion-of-more-buses-all-dressed-alike-20101221-194gk.html|first=Alexandra|last=Smith|title=Out of the blue, an illusion of more buses, all dressed alike|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=22 December 2010}}</ref><ref name=ManlyDaily11Jan13>[http://origin.manly-daily.whereilive.com.au/news/story/blue-over-green-forest-coach-lines-buses/ Blue over green Forest Coach Lines buses] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429234428/http://origin.manly-daily.whereilive.com.au/news/story/blue-over-green-forest-coach-lines-buses/ |date=2013-04-29 }} ''[[Manly Daily]]'' 11 January 2013</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/bus/custom-coaches-rigid-12-metre-any-chassis-bus-livery-guidelines.pdf|title=Livery specification, Custom Coaches rigid 12 metre|author=Transport for NSW|date=October 2013|access-date=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326211009/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/bus/custom-coaches-rigid-12-metre-any-chassis-bus-livery-guidelines.pdf|archive-date=26 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Bus priority infrastructure==\nMany roads in Sydney have bus priority lanes. There are two types of bus lanes in Sydney;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/roads/using-roads/buses/bus-lanes.html|title=Bus lanes|last=NSW|first=Roads and Maritime Services|website=Roads and Maritime Services|access-date=2016-05-02}}</ref>\n* Bus Lane - For use by Taxis, Hire Cars (Not Rentals), Motorcycles, Bicycles, Emergency Vehicles and special purpose vehicles and vehicles also operated by or under the direction of Roads and Maritime Services.\n* Bus Only Lane - For the exclusive use of Buses and authorised special purpose vehicles. These are often used at traffic lights to allow buses to overtake queued traffic.\nMany of them are operational for 24 hours, or during the peak hour. Cameras are often set up along bus lanes and drivers who break rules by driving along bus lanes at dedicated times are fined.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bus lanes|url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/roads/using-roads/buses/bus-lanes.html|website=rms.nsw.gov.au|accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n<mapframe width=\"350\" height=\"350\" text=\"The bus-only roads in Sydney\" longitude=\"151.0483\" latitude=\"-33.8400\" zoom=\"10\">\n[\n{\n  \"type\": \"ExternalData\",\n  \"service\": \"page\",\n  \"title\": \"North-West T-way.map\"\n},\n{\n  \"type\": \"ExternalData\",\n  \"service\": \"page\",\n  \"title\": \"Liverpool\u2013Parramatta T-way.map\"\n},\n{\n  \"type\": \"ExternalData\",\n  \"service\": \"page\",\n  \"title\": \"Moore Park Busway.map\"\n},\n{\n  \"type\": \"ExternalData\",\n  \"service\": \"page\",\n  \"title\": \"Holker Busway.map\"\n},\n{\n \"type\": \"ExternalData\",\n \"service\": \"geoline\",\n \"ids\": \"Q24034546\",\n \"properties\": {\n  \"stroke\": \"#00A7E6\",\n  \"stroke-width\": 5,\n  \"title\": \"[[Bennelong Bridge]]\"\n}\n}\n]\n</mapframe>\nDedicated bus only roads include a separate road in [[Moore Park, New South Wales|Moore Park]] which shadows parts of Alison Road and [[Anzac Parade, Sydney|Anzac Parade]],<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702080034/http://www.sydneybuses.info/news/temporary-closure-of-bus-roadway-from-5-june-26-feb-2015|archivedate=2 July 2015|url=http://www.sydneybuses.info/news/temporary-closure-of-bus-roadway-from-5-june-26-feb-2015|title=Temporary closure of Moore Park Bus Roadway from 5 June - 26 Feb 2015|work=State Transit|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> as well as dedicated roadways at the centre of [[M2 Hills Motorway]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/traffic-chaos-as-bus-catches-on-fire-on-m2-motorway-20150312-142lkq.html|title=Traffic chaos as bus catches on fire on M2 motorway|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=12 March 2015|first=Su-Lin|last=Tan|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> and T-ways.\n\nSydney has three operating transitways (or T-ways):\n*The [[Liverpool\u2013Parramatta T-way]], opened in 2003\n*The [[North-West T-way]], opened in 2007\n*[[Bennelong Bridge]], opened in 2016<ref name=bennelong>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/inner-west/a-camera-has-been-set-up-to-catch-drivers-sneaking-across-the-bennelong-bridge-between-wentworth-point-and-rhodes/news-story/8364b90c27308e64cd53ebb1fe062c09|title=A camera has been set up to catch drivers sneaking across the Bennelong Bridge between Wentworth Point and Rhodes|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 November 2016|accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThese T-ways can only be used by buses or authorised T-way vehicles. Cameras have been set up along the three T-ways and vehicles without authorised access are fined. For Bennelong bridge, separate fines apply to cyclists using the T-way instead of the adjacent shared pedestrian path on the bridge.<ref name=bennelong/>\n\n==Ticketing and fares==\nThe bus network uses the smartcard-based [[Opal ticketing system]]. Opal is also valid on light rail, train and ferry services but separate fares apply for these modes. Opal's bus fares are the same as those for light rail but the fares are not combined when interchanging between the two modes. This is due to change once the [[CBD and South East Light Rail]] opens; all bus passengers interchanging with light rail will only pay one fare, calculated from the start of their trip on one mode to the end of their trip on the other.<ref>{{cite web|title=Opal to go live on light rail months ahead of schedule|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/opal-go-live-light-rail-months-ahead-schedule|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141201221153/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/opal-go-live-light-rail-months-ahead-schedule|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 December 2014|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=24 November 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.transportnsw.info/sites/en/transport-status/news/2014/opal-rollout.page Opal extends to Inner West and Rockdale State Transit bus services] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006071610/http://www.transportnsw.info/sites/en/transport-status/news/2014/opal-rollout.page |date=6 October 2014 }} Transport Info NSW 12 September 2014</ref> Bus drivers also sell non-smartcard Opal single trip tickets - however this facility has been withdrawn from bus regions 4, 7. 8 and 9.<ref>[https://transportnsw.info/news/2019/most-buses-in-north-west-of-sydney-are-moving-to-opal-only-services Most buses in the North West of Sydney are moving to Opal only services] Transport for NSW 16 June 2019</ref> The single trip tickets are more expensive than the standard Opal fare. They are only valid for travel on the bus service on which they are purchased.<ref>{{cite web|title=Opal single trip tickets|url=https://transportnsw.info/tickets-opal/opal/fares-payments/opal-single-tickets|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> The following table lists Opal fares for reusable smartcards and single trip tickets:<ref>{{cite web|title=Opal fares|url=https://transportnsw.info/tickets-opal/opal/fares-payments|website=transportnsw.info|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n{{Opal bus/light rail fares}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Buses in Sydney}}\n* [http://www.transportnsw.info Public transport information \u2013 Transport for NSW]\n* [http://www.legislation.nsw.gov.au/sessionalview/sessional/act/1930-18.pdf Transport Act 1930 (NSW) \u2013 NSW Legislation]\n\n{{List of public transport operators in Sydney}}\n{{AusPTBus}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buses In Sydney}}\n[[Category:Bus transport in Sydney| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Public transit\n| name = Buses in Sydney\n| image = File:Transport for NSW - Buses.png\n| alt = Bus icon\n| imagesize = 220\n| image2 = Transport NSW liveried (2604 ST), operated by Sydney Buses, Bustech VST bodied Scania K280UB on Loftus Street in Circular Quay.jpg\n| caption2 = Scania K280UB with Bustech VST body, in Transport for NSW livery\n| imagesize2 = 250px\n| locale = Greater [[Sydney]]\n| transit_type = [[Bus]] / [[Bus rapid transit]]\n| began_operation = 1905\n| ended_operation = \n| system_length = \n| lines = \n| stations = \n| ridership = \n| annual_ridership = 280.6 million in 2018-19<ref name=\"TfNSW Opal figures\">{{cite web|title=Bus Patronage - Monthly Figures|url=https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/data-and-research/passenger-travel/bus-patronage/bus-patronage-monthly-figures|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n| website = [http://www.transportnsw.info/ transportnsw.info]\n| operator = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Busabout Sydney|Busabout]]\n* [[Busways]]\n* [[Forest Coach Lines|Forest]]\n* [[Hillsbus]]\n* [[Interline Bus Services|Interline]]\n* [[Punchbowl Bus Company]]\n* [[State Transit Authority|State Transit]]\n* [[Transdev NSW|Transdev]]\n* [[Transit Systems Sydney|Transit Systems]]}}\n| owner = [[Transport for NSW]]\n| area served = \n| line_number = \n| start = \n| end = \n| chief_executive = \n| character = \n| vehicles = \n| map = \n| map_state = \n| caption = \n| imagesize3 = 100\n| image3 = File:TfNSW B.svg\n| caption3 = System icon\n}}\n\n[[File:Australian Census 2011 demographic map - Inner Sydney by SA1 - BCP field 7840 One method Bus Persons.svg|right|thumb|Distribution map showing the percentage of the employed population who travel to work by bus only, according to the [[Australian Census|Australian census 2011]].]]\n\n'''Buses''' account for close to six per cent of trips each day in the Australian city of [[Sydney]], New South Wales, forming a key part of the city's public transport system. The network initially evolved from a privately operated system of feeder services to railway stations in the outer suburbs, and a publicly operated network of bus services introduced to replace trams in the inner suburbs. The bus network has undergone major reform in recent years, with the New South Wales Government taking responsibility for route and fare-setting, opening contracts for most routes up to competitive tendering, and introducing more cross-regional services.\n\nThe New South Wales Government's transport authority, [[Transport for NSW]], administers the various bus networks in Sydney.\n* [[Commuter bus]] services including [[Metrobus (Sydney)|Metrobus]] and On Demand routes.\n* [[NightRide]], a network of train replacement services that operates each night between midnight and 5am.\n* [[Sydney Olympic Park bus routes]], a network of nine routes used to convey passengers to major events at the precinct\n* School buses.\nThe networks, except the Olympic Park and On Demand routes, are part of Transport for NSW's [[Opal ticketing system]].\n\nCommuter and school services are assigned to one of [[Sydney Metropolitan Bus Service Contracts|14 contract regions]]. In the 2018-19 financial year, 280.6 million passenger journeys were made on services in Sydney's bus contract regions.<ref name=\"TfNSW Opal figures\"/>\n\n== History ==\nAt the beginning of the 20th century, Sydney's public transport network was composed of a suburban railway and inner-city trams, both operated by the [[New South Wales Government Railways]]. These were complemented by various privately operated ferry services on [[Port Jackson|Sydney Harbour]] and the [[Parramatta River]], and a few horse-drawn services.\n\nThe Railways experimented with a steam-powered bus service from [[Potts Point]] to [[Darlinghurst]] in 1905, but the vehicles quickly proved unsatisfactory and the service was shut down within a year.<ref name=lee>{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Robert|title=Transport: an Australian history|date=2010|publisher=UNSW Press|location=Sydney}}</ref> The city's second bus route ran from [[Newport, New South Wales|Newport]], in the north of the [[Northern Beaches]] district, to [[Manly, New South Wales|Manly]], commencing in 1906. This was operated by the privately owned Manly-Pittwater Motor Omnibus Company. The company did not prosper, however, and the business was wound up in 1908.<ref>{{cite web|last1=JMacR|title=Manly's first bus|url=http://manlylocalstudies.blogspot.com.au/2012/12/manlys-first-bus.html|website=Manly Library Local Studies Blog|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe return of servicemen from [[World War I]] in the late 1910s provided fresh impetus to the motor omnibus industry. Here, suddenly, were thousands of men with experience working with heavy vehicles \u2013 all looking for work.<ref name=nla>{{cite web| first1=Margaret | last1=Simpson | date=2006|title=New South Wales Government and private bus ticket collection | publication-date=1960 | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/192444483 | accessdate=6 March 2016 }}</ref> In 1915, only 15 motorised buses were known to operate in Sydney. By 1929, the city's bus fleet numbered more than 600. A private bus industry, dominated by owner-operators and small family businesses, was taking shape.<ref name=lee />\n\nSeeking to protect the tram system from competition, [[Premier of New South Wales|Premier]] [[Jack Lang (Australian politician)|Jack Lang]] introduced the ''Transport Act 1930'', which empowered a new Metropolitan Transport Trust to shut down private bus routes that competed with trams, trains or other buses. The Railways were also restructured, with the tram system hived off into a new Department of Road Transport & Tramways in 1932.<ref>{{cite web|title=Department of Road Transport & Tramways|url=http://search-cloudfront.records.nsw.gov.au/agencies/537|author=State Records Authority of New South Wales|access-date=3 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201155845/http://search-cloudfront.records.nsw.gov.au/agencies/537|archive-date=1 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Department introduced its first bus service, [[Sydney bus route 144|route 144]] from [[St Leonards, New South Wales|St Leonards]] to Manly, on Christmas Day of that year.\n\nLang's reforms established a structure for the bus network that was to endure for close to a century. On the one hand, the Department \u2013 forerunner to today's [[State Transit Authority]] \u2013 began to shut down its trams and build an extensive bus network serving the inner suburbs and Northern Beaches. On the other, the heavily regulated private operators remained small-scale, relegated to the status of feeder services for the Government's trains. But Lang's draconian Transport Act held at least one benefit for the bus companies: just as the trams were protected from them, so too were they protected from new entrants to the industry.<ref name=lee />\n\n=== From trams to buses ===\nRoute [[Sydney bus route 144|144]] started as a service in the 1920s connecting trains, trams and ferries. But the Department's focus began to shift inexorably towards building its bus network, starting in 1937 when [[Kogarah]]'s steam trams were replaced with [[Trolleybuses in Sydney|trolleybuses]]. Two years later, tram services from Manly were replaced with buses. In 1948, a recommendation was handed to the Department that the entire network be replaced with buses. Though initially controversial, the move to a bus network secured broad political support and was completed between 1957 and 1961. The Department, renamed 'Government Transport' in 1952, became an operator of buses only.<ref name=lee /><ref>{{cite web|title=Department of Government Tram and Omnibus Services (1952) / Department of Government Transport (1952-1972)|url=http://search-cloudfront.records.nsw.gov.au/agencies/538|author=State Records Authority of New South Wales}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFor much of the 20th century, land use planning in Sydney restricted development to corridors within a short distance of the existing railway lines. This discipline broke down in the 1980s, however, when the [[Wran ministry (1983-84)|Wran Government]] released [[Sydney Into Its Third Century|new areas for development]] far from existing rail lines.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sydney Into Its Third Century: Metropolitan Strategy for the Sydney Region |year=1988|author=Department of Environment & Planning|location=Sydney|author-link=Department of Planning and Environment (New South Wales)}}</ref><ref name=\"dos\">{{cite web |url= http://dictionaryofsydney.org/entry/planning |title = Planning | first1=Paul | last1=Ashton | first2=Robert | last2=Freestone | date = 2008 |work = Dictionary of Sydney |publisher = Dictionary of Sydney Trust}}</ref> This meant that buses outside of the inner-city, government-operated network, would play an increasing role in meeting Sydney's transport needs.\n\nLang's model divided the city into hundreds of exclusive fiefdoms and did not allow for cross-regional services. Some private operators responded with joint ventures under the \"Red Arrow\" brand, agreeing to jointly operate routes between major centres in each other's territories. Some of these routes survive in whole or part today.\n\n=== Contracts ===\nFrom 1930 until 1990, private bus companies in Sydney operated as licensed local monopolies, with a relatively free hand to set fares, determine routes, set service levels and choose vehicles. The [[Greiner-Murray ministry (1988-91)|Greiner Government]] changed this with the introduction of the ''Passenger Transport Act 1990''. Although the government was loth to challenge the operators' local dominance, it insisted on forming contractual relationships between bus companies and the Department of Transport. These formed the basis for improvements to service standards and \u2013 in time \u2013 would allow the Government to consolidate the industry and create a truly integrated public transport network. The Government also dismantled one of the shibboleths of the Lang era, allowing [[Forest Coach Lines]] and [[Westbus]] to run direct services to the City, rather than just the nearest train station. In 1992, an inbound bus lane was installed on the [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]] to facilitate the additional services.\n\n=== Unsworth review ===\nDevelopment in the [[Hills District|Hills]] and [[Forest District (Sydney)|Forest]] districts, far from railway lines, meant that long-distance private bus services poured across the Harbour Bridge to the City each morning. The growth of employment centres outside of the City and inner suburbs, including the growing significance of Parramatta, meant that more and more commuters were making cross-regional, rather than suburb-to-city, trips. Finally, the profusion of bus networks \u2013 in 2004, they numbered more than 80 \u2013 was confusing to planners and passengers alike. In return for their acceptance of limits to their operations, the small family-owned bus companies had enjoyed immunity from competition themselves. The result was a disparity in fares, vehicles and service quality across Sydney.\n\nThe Government commissioned a report into the bus network from former premier [[Barrie Unsworth]]. This report, released in 2004, formed a blueprint for major changes to the bus network, including:\n* harmonisation of private and State Transit fares\n* consolidation of bus regions and competitive tendering for rights to operate\n* introduction of new, cross-regional routes.\n\nConsolidation of bus contract regions, from more than 80 to just 15, forced the amalgamation of decades-old bus companies and cleared the way for the entry of players from interstate and overseas.\n\nStarting in October 2008 a number of Metrobus routes were introduced.\n\nCross-regional connectivity received further boosts with the completion of dedicated T-way networks, between [[Liverpool-Parramatta T-way|Liverpool and Parramatta]] and between [[North-West T-way|Parramatta, Blacktown and Rouse Hill]].\n\n==Contract regions==\n{{main|Sydney Metropolitan Bus Service Contracts}}\nMost services are provided under a service contract between the operator and Transport for NSW. There are 14 contract regions, each of which is tied to a geographical area.\n\n{{Sydney bus contract regions}}\n\n===Routes===\n====B1 Mona Vale to Sydney CBD ====\n{{main|B-Line (Sydney)}}\nThis is a limited stops route operating in the Northern Beaches region of Sydney. It is operated with a dedicated fleet of double deck buses.<ref name=TfNSW091115>[http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/new-b-line-transform-northern-beaches-bus-travel New B-Line to transform Northern Beaches Bus travel] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202040804/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/new-b-line-transform-northern-beaches-bus-travel |date=2 February 2016 }} Transport for NSW 9 November 2015</ref>\n\n====T80 Liverpool to Parramatta====\n{{main|Liverpool-Parramatta T-way}}\nThis is a [[bus rapid transit]] route operating in the south western part of Sydney, mostly along dedicated bus-only roads.<ref name=T80>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180318091043/http://www.transitsystems.com.au/sydney/news/166-transit-systems-secures-region-6-bus-contract Transit Systems secures Region 6 Bus Contract (Final Paragraph)] Transit Systems</ref>\n\n====North-West T-way====\n{{main|North-West T-way}}\nA variety of routes operate along various sections of this T-Way, including some express services to the CBD.\n[[File:Busways (mo 9707) and Metrobus livered (mo 5317) operated by Hillsbus at Castle Hill Interchange (1).jpg|alt=|210x210px|A Metrobus Volvo B7RLE operating on route M60 at Castle Hill|thumb]]\n\n====Metrobus routes====\n{{main|Metrobus (Sydney)}}\nMetrobus routes operate in various parts of Sydney. The original Metrobus routes run along major inner city corridors, passing through the Sydney central business district without terminating there. Later routes operate in areas further out from the city centre, connecting major suburban precincts. Metrobus routes are increasingly being debranded into normal routes, with many routes having now lost the M prefix, in case of confusion with metro services.\n\n====Other routes====\nMany other routes operate throughout Sydney. Most of these routes are classified with three-digit route numbers based on the area of the city they operate in:\n\n*100 series \u2013 [[Northern Beaches]]\n*200 series \u2013 [[Forest District (Sydney)|Northern Districts]] and [[North Shore (Sydney)|North Shore]]\n*300 series \u2013 [[Eastern Suburbs (Sydney)|Eastern Suburbs]]\n*400 series \u2013 [[Inner West]] and Southern Suburbs\n*500 series \u2013 North West\n*600 series \u2013 Western Suburbs and [[Hills District]] (T-way)\n*700 series \u2013 Outer Western Suburbs and [[Hills District]] (T-way)\n*800 series \u2013 Outer South-Western Suburbs\n*900 series \u2013 [[St George (Sydney)|St George]]/[[Sutherland Shire|Sutherland]] and South West\n\nSpecial services are denoted by letter prefixes in their route number:\n\n* '''M''' - Metrobus services (most M routes have been renumbered into normal 3-digit numbers as of 2020)\n* '''B''' - B-Line services\n* '''E''' or '''X''' \u2013 Express service (used by State Transit (regions 7, 8 and 9) and Transit Systems (region 6); \"E\" is used for region 8 services, \"X\" elsewhere)\n* '''L''' \u2013 Limited Stops service (used by State Transit (regions 7, 8 and 9) and Transit Systems (region 6). Some Limited Stops routes use normal three-digit numbers)\n* '''T''' \u2013 Services operating, at least for the most part, via a T-Way (only [[Liverpool-Parramatta T-way|T80]] left with those operating on the [[North-West T-way]] having been renumbered into normal 3-digit numbers as of 2019)\n* '''S''' \u2013 \"Shopper Hopper\" route (used for some private operators' routes that typically run between morning and afternoon peaks, Monday-Friday only)\n\nAdditionally, [[NightRide]] services are prefixed with '''N''' (although these services are not provided under a region contract).\n\nSome routes have a suffix to their route numbers instead of prefixes:\n* '''N''' - Overnight services for the routes concerned with some minor variations (used since 2018)\n* '''X''' - Express service equivalents for the routes concerned (used by Hillsbus and since 2018, State Transit. Hillsbus uses this suffix for services via [[Lane Cove Tunnel]]).\n*'''Any other letter''' - Used by some operators to denote the destination of routes with more than two termini. For example, the suffixes W and K are used by [[Busabout Sydney|Busabout]] to denote variants of routes 884 and 883 that service [[Wedderburn, New South Wales|Wedderburn]] and [[Kentlyn, New South Wales|Kentlyn]] respectively.\n\nState Transit and Transit Systems Region 6 school bus services are suffixed with '''N''' ([[Sydney Metropolitan Bus_Service Contracts#Region_8|Region 8]]), '''S''' ([[Sydney Metropolitan Bus_Service Contracts#Region_6|Region 6]]), '''E''' ([[Sydney Metropolitan Bus_Service Contracts#Region_9|Region 9]]) and '''W''' ([[Sydney Metropolitan Bus_Service Contracts#Region_7|Region 7]]). However, bus destinations boards do not show the suffix due to technical limitations.\n\n==Rail replacement bus services==\nRail replacement bus services in Sydney replace or supplement train services, but charge train or metro fares.\n\n===Station Link===\n\n[[File:Station Link mo6981 SL1 Chatswood May 2019 2.jpg|thumb|A Station Link bus outside [[Chatswood railway station|Chatswood station]]]]\nFrom September 2018 to May 2019, Station Link bus services replaced rail services between Chatswood and Epping, while the [[Epping to Chatswood rail link]] was converted and upgraded to metro services. The main service SL1, operated frequently throughout the day, stopping at all stops between Chatswood and Epping.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transportnsw.info/plan/station-link|title=Station Link|website=Transport Info NSW|accessdate=8 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115021225/https://transportnsw.info/plan/station-link|archivedate=15 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The other services SL2 - SL7, operated only during weekday peak hours. Fares on these bus routes were charged at train rates. The services were jointly operated by [[Transdev NSW]] and [[Hillsbus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.mysydney.nsw.gov.au/documents/FAQStationLink.pdf|title=Upgrade of the Epping to Chatswood line - Station Link bus services|website=MySydney - NSW Government|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608084047/http://data.mysydney.nsw.gov.au/documents/FAQStationLink.pdf|archivedate=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTwo weeks before its cessation, over 4.3 million trips had been taken on Station Link.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sydneymetro.info/article/upgrade-complete-between-epping-and-chatswood|title=Upgrade complete between Epping and Chatswood|publisher=Sydney Metro|date=23 May 2019|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===North West Night Bus===\n{{more|Metro North West Line#North West Night Bus}}\nFrom 26 May to 5 November 2019, North West Night Bus operated on two supplementary late night bus services, NW1 and NW2, to supplement the Metro North West Line metro operations on Sunday to Wednesday nights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transportnsw.info/plan/north-west-night-bus|title=North West Night Bus|website=Transport Info NSW|access-date=25 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025103909/https://transportnsw.info/north-west-night-bus|archive-date=25 October 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> They are successors to the Station Link, which was discontinued due to the opening of Sydney Metro. Metro fares were charged on these bus routes. Like Station Link, both Night Bus services were also operated by Transdev and Hillsbus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transportnsw.info/documents/timetables/36-NW1-Tallawong-to-Chatswood-20190526.pdf|title=NW1 Timetable - May 2019|website=Transport Info NSW|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505210504/https://transportnsw.info/documents/timetables/36-NW1-Tallawong-to-Chatswood-20190526.pdf|archivedate=5 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://transportnsw.info/documents/timetables/36-NW2-Tallawong-to-Chatswood-Limited-Stops-20190526.pdf|title=NW2 Timetable - May 2019|website=Transport Info NSW|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505210704/https://transportnsw.info/documents/timetables/36-NW2-Tallawong-to-Chatswood-Limited-Stops-20190526.pdf|archivedate=5 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Route 535===\nThe [[Carlingford railway line|T6 Carlingford Line]] ceased operations on 5 January 2020, and a replacement bus service, route 535, commenced operations on the same day. It charges train fares and runs between Carlingford and Parramatta.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parramattalightrail.nsw.gov.au/news/t6-carlingford-line-close-5-january-2020|title=T6 Carlingford Line to close 5 January 2020|publisher=Parramatta Light Rail|date=9 October 2019|accessdate=6 January 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124010032/http://www.parramattalightrail.nsw.gov.au/news/t6-carlingford-line-close-5-january-2020|archivedate=24 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It is operated by [[Hillsbus]].\n\n===Bankstown Line replacement bus services===\nBeginning in December 2019, bus services will operate between Bankstown and Sydenham during certain periods so that the [[Bankstown Line]] could be converted and upgraded to metro services. This procedure will continue until 2023, after which that section of the line will be temporarily closed to complete its integration into the [[Sydney Metro City & Southwest|City & Southwest Metro Line]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/rail-line-closures-to-force-100-000-commuters-a-day-to-catch-buses-20190718-p528eg.html|title=Rail line closure to force 100,000 commuters a day to catch buses|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=18 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Trackwork Buses===\nBuses are also frequently used to replace train lines that are closed for trackwork, mainly on weekends or late nights. These replacement services are contracted out to a bus company by [[Sydney Trains]]. Because it is impossible for one bus company to provide enough buses, the company will then subcontract some of the work to other bus companies.\nOn most of these services, no fare is charged as these routes are not programmed into the Opal system and there is no requirement for buses provided to have Opal equipment installed. However, this is slowly changing, with some rail replacement services now having Opal set up to charge rail fares.\n\nThe routes are defined by Sydney Trains, with route numbers consisting of one or two numbers, optionally followed by A (usually indicates short working variant), then the train line the route replaces. Examples include 35T3, 61T8 etc.\n\n==On Demand services==\nSince late 2017 a number of On Demand services have been introduced throughout the metropolitan and outer metropolitan bus regions. These are not part of the [[Opal card]] ticketing system and most do not accept concession fares. However, [[Opal card#OpalPay|OpalPay]] and concession fares can be used and accepted on some of these services.<ref>[https://transportnsw.info/tickets-opal/opal/opalpay How OpalPay works] Transport for NSW</ref>\n\nAs of November 2019, the on demand services in Greater Sydney are:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transportnsw.info/travel-info/ways-to-get-around/on-demand-public-transport|title=On Demand public transport|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Central Coast (New South Wales)|Central Coast]] on demand service - operated by Community Transport Central Coast's CoastConnect\n*[[Edmondson Park, New South Wales|Edmondson Park]] on demand service - operated by [[Interline Bus Services]]' Interline Connect\n*[[Inner West]] on demand service - operated by [[Transit Systems]]' [[Bridj]]<ref>[https://transportnsw.info/travel-info/ways-to-get-around/on-demand/inner-west  Inner West On Demand service] Transport for NSW</ref>\n*[[Illawarra]] on demand service - operated by [[Premier Transport Group|Premier Motor Service]]'s Premier Illawarra On Demand (PODPI)\n*[[Macquarie Park, New South Wales|Macquarie Park]] on demand service - operated by [[Keolis Downer]]'s Keoride\n*[[Norwest, New South Wales|Norwest]] on demand service - started May 2019 - operated by [[Hillsbus]]' MetroConnect\n*[[Northern Beaches]] on demand service - operated by Keoride\n*[[The Ponds, New South Wales|The Ponds]] on demand service - started May 2019 - operated by [[Busways]]' Cooee Busways\n\nOther on demand services have also been trialled but have since ceased.\n*[[Bankstown]] on demand service - operated by [[Punchbowl Bus Company]]'s Punchbowl On Demand (POD) - ceased 14 October 2018.<ref>[http://www.punchbowlbus.com.au/news Catch The Pod will be ceasing at 11:59PM, 14 October 2018] Punchbowl Bus Co.</ref>\n*[[Carlingford, New South Wales|Carlingford]] and [[North Rocks, New South Wales|North Rocks]] on demand service - operated by [[Hillsbus]]' OurBus - ceased 24 May 2019.<ref>[https://transportnsw.info/travel-info/ways-to-get-around/on-demand/carlingford-north-rocks Carlingford and North Rocks On Demand service] Transport for NSW</ref>\n*[[Eastern Suburbs (Sydney)|Eastern Suburbs]] on demand service - operated by Bridj, formerly by [[Transdev Australasia|Transdev]]'s RIDE Plus until August 2018 - ceased 20 December 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://transportnsw.info/news/2019/eastern-suburbs-on-demand-trial-to-end-20-december|title=Eastern Suburbs On Demand trial to end 20 December|last=Transport for NSW|first=Customer Experience Division|website=transportnsw.info|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n*[[Manly, New South Wales|Manly]] on demand service - operated by RIDE Plus - ceased 24 May 2019.<ref>[https://transportnsw.info/travel-info/ways-to-get-around/on-demand/manly Manly on demand service] Transport for NSW]</ref>\n*[[Sutherland Shire]] on demand Service - operated by [[Transdev Australasia|Transdev]]'s Transdev Link ceased 17 November 2019.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20191117061438/https://www.transdevlink.com.au/ Transport on demand. Ready when you are.] TransdevLink]</ref>\n\n*[[Wetherill Park, New South Wales|Wetherill Park]] on demand service - operated by Bridj - ceased 3 August 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transportnsw.info/travel-info/ways-to-get-around/on-demand-public-transport/wetherill-park-on-demand-service|title=Wetherill Park On Demand service|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=7 August 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807030009/https://transportnsw.info/travel-info/ways-to-get-around/on-demand-public-transport/wetherill-park-on-demand-service|archivedate=7 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Patronage==\nThe following table lists patronage figures for the network of contract regions (in millions of journeys) during the corresponding financial year. Australia's financial years start on 1 July and end on 30 June. Major events that affected the number of journeys made or how patronage is measured are included as notes.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; white-space:nowrap;\"\n|+Bus patronage in Sydney by financial year\n! Year \n| 2010-11 || 2011-12 || 2012-13 || 2013-14 || 2014-15 || 2015-16 || 2016-17 || 2017-18 || 2018-19\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n! Patronage<br><span style=\"font-size:90%\">(millions)</span>\n| 198.7\n| 203.3\n| 204.6\n| 209.0\n| 232.0<br>{{efn|name=2014-15 1}}{{efn|name=2014-15 2}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a}}\n| 253.1<br>{{efn|name=2016-17}}\n| 264.3\n| 280.6\n|- style=\"font-size:85%\"\n! Reference\n<!--2010-11-->\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Transport for NSW Annual Report 2013-14|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/publications/annual_reports/tfnsw-annual-report-2013-2014.pdf|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=1 August 2016|page=395|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529174646/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/publications/annual_reports/tfnsw-annual-report-2013-2014.pdf|archive-date=29 May 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n<!--2011-12 to 2014-15-->\n|colspan=\"4\"|<ref>{{cite web|title=Transport for NSW Annual Report 2014-15|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/publications/annual_reports/tfnsw-annual-report-2014-15-volume-1.pdf|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=1 Au